SIMPLE: graduate
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Graduate
<hw>Grad"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Graduated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Graduating</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
F. <ets>graduer</ets>. See <er>Graduate</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Grade</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To mark with degrees; to divide into regular steps,
grades, or intervals, as the scale of a thermometer, a scheme of
punishment or rewards, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To admit or elevate to a certain grade or degree;
esp., in a college or university, to admit, at the close of the course,
to an honorable standing defined by a diploma; <as>as, he was graduated
at Yale College</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To prepare gradually; to arrange, temper, or modify
by degrees or to a certain degree; to determine the degrees of; <as>as,
to graduate the heat of an oven</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dyers advance and graduate their colors with salts.</q>
<rj><qau>Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To bring to a certain degree of
consistency, by evaporation, as a fluid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Graduating engine</b></col>, <cd>a dividing engine. See
<cref>Dividing</cref> engine, under <er>Dividing</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Graduate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Graduate
<hw>Grad"u*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pass by
degrees; to change gradually; to shade off; <as>as, sandstone which
<ex>graduates</ex> into gneiss; carnelian sometimes <ex>graduates</ex>
into quartz.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>To taper, as the tail of certain
birds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To take a degree in a college or university; to
become a graduate; to receive a diploma.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>graduated</qex> at Oxford.</q>
<rj><qau>Latham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was brought to their bar and asked where he had
<qex>graduated</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Graduate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Graduate
<hw>Grad"u*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>graduatus</ets>, p. p. of graduare to admit to a degree, fr. L.
<ets>gradus</ets> grade. See <er>Grade</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>One who has received an academical or professional
degree; one who has completed the prescribed course of study in any
school or institution of learning.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A graduated cup, tube, flask, or cylinder; a glass
measuring container used by apothecaries and chemists. See under
<er>Graduated</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Graduate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Graduate
<hw>Grad"u*ate</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Graduate</er>, <pos>n.
& v.</pos>]</ety> <def>Arranged by successive steps or degrees;
graduated.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Beginning with the genus, passing through all the
<qex>graduate</qex>⟦br⟧
and subordinate stages.</q> <rj><qau>Tatham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Graduated</ent>⟦br⟧
